arXiv:2601.19897 • January 2025

Self-Distillation Enables Continual Learning

On-policy learning from expert demonstrations via in-context self-distillation, eliminating the need for reward engineering while reducing catastrophic forgetting

Target Audience: ML researchers and practitioners working on LLM post-training, continual learning, knowledge distillation, and RL from demonstrations
Detail Level Overview
What How Details Code
§ 0

TL;DR

Executive Summary

Self-Distillation Fine-Tuning (SDFT) solves a long-standing gap in continual learning: how to get the forgetting-reduction benefits of on-policy learning when you only have expert demonstrations and no reward function. The trick is elegant -- use the same model as both teacher (conditioned on demonstrations via in-context learning) and student (query only), then minimize reverse KL divergence on student-generated trajectories. This is provably equivalent to on-policy RL with an implicit reward derived from the demonstration-conditioned model, sidestepping the need for explicit reward engineering or inverse RL. Across skill learning, knowledge acquisition, and sequential multi-task settings on Qwen2.5-7B, SDFT consistently achieves higher new-task accuracy than SFT (e.g., 70.2% vs 66.2% on Science QA) while preserving roughly 65% prior capabilities versus SFT's 53-60%. The method's advantage scales with model size, suggesting it will become more powerful as foundation models grow.

Bottom Line

If you need to teach a sufficiently large language model new skills or knowledge from demonstrations without destroying what it already knows, SDFT is the current best approach -- it turns any demonstration dataset into on-policy learning without requiring reward engineering, at the cost of roughly 2.5x compute.

§ 1

Core Method: Self-Distillation Fine-Tuning

Key Insight

SDFT lets a language model learn new skills by having it teach itself: the same model, when shown an example answer, guides its own training, achieving 70.2% on new tasks while retaining 64.5% on old ones (vs. SFT's 66.2% / 53.4%).

Most methods for teaching a language model new skills require either curating large datasets of correct answers (supervised fine-tuning) or training a separate reward model (reinforcement learning). SDFT sidesteps both. It uses the same model in two roles at once: a teacher and a student.

The teacher version of the model gets to see a worked example alongside the question. With that example in its context window, it already produces high-quality answers thanks to in-context learning, the ability large language models have to adapt their behavior based on what they see in the prompt. The student version sees only the question with no example. Training then nudges the student to match the teacher's output distribution, so the knowledge embedded in the demonstration gets internalized into the model's weights.

Think of it like a student who is allowed to look at a solved problem on the board during a practice test. At first, she needs the solved problem to know what to do. But after enough practice, she can solve similar problems on her own without the reference. The demonstration is the solved problem on the board; training is the practice that makes it stick.

Critically, because the teacher is nearly the same model as the student (just augmented with the demo), the knowledge transfer is gentle. The student does not have to radically reshape its internal representations the way it would if forced to mimic a completely different, stronger model. This gentleness is exactly what prevents catastrophic forgetting of previously learned skills.

Core Idea

The same model serves as both teacher (with demo) and student (without demo), so new knowledge is absorbed gently without overwriting old knowledge.

Analogy

Like a student who first solves problems by glancing at a worked example on the board, then gradually learns to solve them independently. The reference is removed, but the understanding remains.

Figure 2: Self-Distillation Fine-Tuning architecture and policy landscape
What This Shows

The left panel explains HOW SDFT works mechanistically: a single LLM plays dual roles. As teacher, it conditions on expert demonstrations and 'knows' the right answer via in-context learning. As student, it only sees the query and must learn to produce the right answer without demonstrations. Training minimizes the reverse KL between student and teacher on the student's own generated outputs (on-policy). The right panel explains WHY this approach avoids forgetting: the teacher (demonstration-conditioned model) is much closer to the base policy in KL-divergence space than the raw demonstrator/expert data would be. This means the student only needs to make small, conservative updates to match the teacher, staying in the low-KL trust region around the base policy.

How to Read This

Left Panel Flow: Query enters the LLM. In Student Mode (top), it produces distribution P without seeing demonstrations. In Teacher Mode (bottom), it sees Query + Demonstration and produces Q. The loss E[log P/Q] pushes P toward Q, and gradients only update the student parameters
Right Panel Interpretation: The contour lines show distance (KL divergence) from the base policy. The Demonstrator (raw expert data) is far from the base policy (high KL ~1.0). But conditioning the same model on the demonstration produces a Teacher that is much closer to the base (lower KL ~0.4-0.5). SDFT then distills to this closer target, staying near the base
Key Mechanism: The crucial insight is that in-context learning transforms a distant expert signal into a nearby teacher signal - the 'conditioning' arrow on the right shows this transformation from demonstrator to teacher
Visual Punchline: On the right panel, notice how SDFT (light blue) ends up very close to the Base Policy, while the Demonstrator is far away - this geometric proximity is why SDFT avoids forgetting
Key Takeaway

By using in-context learning to create a demonstration-conditioned teacher from the same model, SDFT converts a far-away expert signal into a nearby teacher signal, enabling on-policy learning that stays close to the base policy and thus avoids catastrophic forgetting.

Technical Details

Prerequisites:

  • Basic understanding of KL divergence as a measure of distance between probability distributions
  • Understanding of in-context learning in LLMs (model changes behavior when given examples in the prompt)
  • Concept of on-policy vs off-policy learning (training on model's own outputs vs external data)

Common Confusions:

  • Are the student and teacher different models?: No - they are the SAME model with different inputs. The teacher sees the query plus a demonstration; the student sees only the query. This is the 'self' in self-distillation.
  • Why is reverse KL (student || teacher) used instead of forward KL?: Reverse KL requires sampling from the student (on-policy), which is critical for continual learning. Forward KL would require sampling from the teacher (off-policy), losing the on-policy benefit.
  • What does 'conditioning' mean in the right panel?: It refers to the process of providing a demonstration in the LLM's context window. This transforms the distant demonstrator distribution into a closer teacher distribution without changing model parameters.

Technical Details

SDFT defines two distributions from the same model. The teacher distribution \(\pi(y|x,c)\) is obtained by conditioning the model on both the query \(x\) and a demonstration \(c\), provided through in-context learning via a structured prompt template: ‘<Question> This is an example for a response: <Demo> Now answer with a response of your own, including thinking process:’. The student distribution \(\pi_\theta(y|x)\) is the model conditioned only on the query.

Training minimizes the reverse KL divergence between student and teacher. The reverse direction is chosen deliberately: \(D_\text{KL}(\pi_\theta(y|x) \| \pi(y|x,c))\) forces the student to be mode-seeking, concentrating its probability mass on the teacher's high-probability outputs rather than trying to cover all of the teacher's modes. This is standard in variational inference and avoids the student spreading itself too thin.

To stabilize training, the teacher's weights are updated as an exponential moving average (EMA) of the student's weights rather than being frozen. This means the teacher co-evolves with the student, preventing a growing gap between the two that could destabilize gradients.

The training is on-policy: at each step, the student generates its own trajectories (completions), and the loss is computed on those trajectories. This is critical because it means the student is always receiving feedback on the outputs it would actually produce, not on pre-generated data that may be far from its current distribution.

Compared to standard SFT, which directly maximizes log-likelihood of teacher-generated outputs, SDFT has two key structural advantages for continual learning. First, the KL objective penalizes deviation from the teacher rather than forcing exact imitation, allowing the student to retain its own style and prior knowledge. Second, the teacher is only a gentle perturbation of the student (empirically 0.68 nats divergence vs. 1.26 nats for SFT targets from the base model, as shown in Section 3.2), so the gradient signal does not push the student far from its current state.

The authors compare against several baselines: standard SFT, DFT (distillation fine-tuning with importance sampling correction), SFT+Re-invoke (rehearsal with regenerated old-task data), CPT (continued pre-training on raw text), and Oracle RAG (retrieval augmented generation with ground-truth context). SDFT outperforms all non-oracle methods across skill learning, knowledge acquisition, and multi-task continual learning (Tables 1-3).

Ablation results in Figure 6 show a clear hierarchy: on-policy SDFT > offline distillation (using pre-generated teacher outputs) > SFT from teacher outputs. This confirms that both the distillation objective and the on-policy sampling are independently important, and their combination is what makes SDFT effective.

\[ \mathcal{L}_{\text{SDFT}} = D_{KL}(\pi_\theta(\cdot|x) \| \pi(\cdot|x,c)) \]
  • \(\pi_\theta\): Student distribution, model conditioned only on query \(x\)
  • \(\pi(\cdot|x,c)\): Teacher distribution, same model conditioned on query \(x\) and demonstration \(c\)
  • \(x\): Input query
  • \(c\): Demonstration (example answer provided via in-context learning)
  • \(D_\text{KL}\): Reverse KL divergence (student \(\|\) teacher)
\[ \theta_{\text{teacher}}^{(t+1)} = \alpha \cdot \theta_{\text{student}}^{(t)} + (1-\alpha) \cdot \theta_{\text{teacher}}^{(t)} \]
  • \(\theta_\text{teacher}\): Teacher model weights
  • \(\theta_\text{student}\): Student model weights
  • \(\alpha\): EMA coefficient (in \(\{0.01, 0.02, 0.05\}\))
  • \(t\): Training step index
Design Decisions
  • Reverse KL (student || teacher) chosen over forward KL to make the student mode-seeking, concentrating on the teacher's best outputs rather than trying to cover all modes.
  • EMA teacher rather than frozen teacher to prevent growing divergence between teacher and student during training.
  • On-policy sampling (student generates its own trajectories) rather than using pre-generated teacher outputs, ensuring feedback is always relevant to the student's current behavior.
  • Prompt template includes 'including thinking process' to encourage the teacher to produce reasoning chains, not just final answers.

SDFT Training Loop (Python) 
# SDFT Training Loop
import torch
from transformers import AutoModelForCausalLM
from copy import deepcopy

# Initialize
student = AutoModelForCausalLM.from_pretrained('Qwen/Qwen2.5-7B-Instruct')
teacher = deepcopy(student)  # Teacher starts as copy of student
optimizer = torch.optim.AdamW(student.parameters(), lr=1e-5)

# Prompt template
TEMPLATE = (
    "{question}\n"
    "This is an example for a response: {demo}\n"
    "Now answer with a response of your own, including thinking process:"
)

for step, (question, demo) in enumerate(dataloader):
    # 1. Student generates on-policy trajectories (no demo)
    with torch.no_grad():
        student_outputs = student.generate(question, max_length=2048, do_sample=True)
    
    # 2. Teacher scores trajectories (with demo via ICL)
    teacher_input = TEMPLATE.format(question=question, demo=demo)
    with torch.no_grad():
        teacher_logprobs = teacher.log_prob(student_outputs, context=teacher_input)
    
    # 3. Student computes its own log-probs on same trajectories
    student_logprobs = student.log_prob(student_outputs, context=question)
    
    # 4. Reverse KL loss: D_KL(student || teacher)
    # = E_student[log student - log teacher]
    loss = (student_logprobs - teacher_logprobs).mean()
    
    # 5. Backprop and update student
    optimizer.zero_grad()
    loss.backward()
    optimizer.step()
    
    # 6. EMA update teacher
    alpha = 0.02
    with torch.no_grad():
        for t_param, s_param in zip(teacher.parameters(), student.parameters()):
            t_param.data = alpha * s_param.data + (1 - alpha) * t_param.data
Practical Tips ▼
  • The teacher prompt template matters: including 'including thinking process' in the template significantly improves quality of teacher outputs by eliciting chain-of-thought reasoning.
  • Monitor KL divergence between student and teacher during training. If it grows beyond ~1.5 nats, the EMA alpha may be too small (teacher is lagging too far behind).
  • The method requires strong ICL capability in the base model. At 3B parameters, SDFT underperforms SFT (-3.3 points), so use models >= 7B.
  • Watch for the student copying teacher artifacts like 'Based on the text...' phrasing. Fix by masking the loss on the first few generated tokens.
  • Computational cost is ~2.5x FLOPs and ~4x wall-clock vs SFT due to on-policy generation, but this can replace multi-stage pipelines (SFT + RL), making total cost comparable.
  • A single demonstration per task is sufficient. The demo does not need to be perfect; it just needs to illustrate the desired behavior pattern.
Known Failure Modes ▼
  • Student copies teacher phrasing artifacts: Generated outputs contain phrases like 'Based on the text...' or 'As shown in the example...' that reference the demonstration Solution: Mask the loss on the first N generated tokens so the student is not penalized for deviating from the teacher's opening phrasing.
  • SDFT underperforms SFT on small models: At 3B parameters, SDFT scores lower than SFT by ~3 points Solution: The method requires strong in-context learning capability. Use models with >= 7B parameters where ICL is reliable.
  • Teacher drift: Training becomes unstable, loss oscillates wildly Solution: Reduce EMA alpha (e.g., from 0.05 to 0.01) so the teacher changes more slowly, or increase the EMA update frequency.
  • OOM on generation: GPU runs out of memory during student on-policy generation Solution: Reduce max_generation_length from 2048 or use gradient checkpointing. Generation and training can be done in separate forward passes.
§ 2

Theoretical Foundation: Inverse RL Interpretation

Key Insight

SDFT is mathematically equivalent to on-policy reinforcement learning where the reward is implicitly defined by how much better the model performs when shown an example, eliminating the need for an explicit reward model.

Reinforcement learning for language models typically requires someone (a human or another model) to assign explicit scores to outputs. SDFT avoids this entirely. The paper proves that the self-distillation process is secretly doing RL, with the reward signal hiding in plain sight.

The implicit reward for any output is simply the log-probability difference between the teacher (model with example) and the current student (model without example). If the teacher thinks an output is much more likely than the student does, that output gets a high reward — meaning it is exactly the kind of output the example was meant to teach. If teacher and student already agree, the reward is near zero — meaning there is nothing new to learn from this output.

This is like learning to cook by comparing your dish to a reference recipe. You do not need a food critic (explicit reward model). The gap between “what the recipe produces” and “what you currently produce” is itself the feedback. The bigger the gap for a particular technique, the more you need to practice it.

The theoretical connection runs through trust-region policy optimization. Each SDFT update corresponds to one step of constrained policy improvement, where the constraint ensures the model does not change too much in a single step. This is why SDFT naturally avoids catastrophic forgetting: it is structurally identical to conservative policy updates in RL, which are specifically designed to prevent drastic behavioral changes.

Core Idea

The reward signal is implicit: it is the log-probability gap between the model with and without the demonstration. No separate reward model is needed.

Analogy

Like learning to cook by comparing your dish to a reference recipe. The gap between the recipe's result and your current result IS the feedback, with no food critic needed.

Technical Details

The IRL interpretation begins from the trust-region RL objective. At iteration \(k\), the next policy is obtained by solving a constrained optimization problem that maximizes expected reward while staying close to the current policy.

The optimal solution to this problem has a known closed form: the next policy is proportional to the current policy re-weighted by exponentiated rewards. By taking the logarithm and rearranging, one can extract the implicit reward as the log-ratio of the optimal next policy to the current policy, scaled by the inverse temperature \(\beta\).

The central theoretical move is what the authors call the ICL Assumption: the teacher distribution \(\pi(y|x,c)\), obtained by conditioning the model on the demonstration, approximates the optimal next policy \(\pi^*_{k+1}(y|x)\). Under this assumption, the implicit reward becomes \(r(y,x,c) = \log \pi(y|x,c) - \log \pi_k(y|x)\), which is simply the log-probability ratio between teacher and student.

This reward decomposes at the token level. For each token \(y_t\) in a sequence, the per-token reward is \(r_t = \log \pi(y_t|y_{<t},x,c) - \log \pi_k(y_t|y_{<t},x)\). This is semantically meaningful: tokens where the teacher strongly disagrees with the student receive larger rewards, focusing learning on the specific behaviors the demonstration is meant to teach.

The policy gradient under this formulation takes the REINFORCE form, where the reward-weighted gradient of the student's log-probability drives the update. The authors show that this is algebraically equivalent to the gradient of the reverse KL divergence \(D_\text{KL}(\pi_\theta \| \pi(\cdot|x,c))\), establishing that minimizing reverse KL is identical to on-policy RL with the implicit reward.

This equivalence has several important implications. First, it explains why on-policy sampling is crucial: the policy gradient estimator requires expectations under the current policy, not an old one. Second, it explains why SDFT outperforms offline distillation: offline methods use stale trajectories, introducing bias in the gradient estimator. Third, the trust-region structure (KL constraint) explains the natural continual learning properties, since the policy changes conservatively at each step.

The connection to inverse RL is that rewards are not given but inferred from the teacher's behavior. The teacher's demonstration implicitly defines what good behavior looks like, and the log-ratio extracts a reward signal that captures exactly how the student should change. This is complementary to standard RL approaches: RL requires explicit rewards but allows arbitrary optimization, while SDFT requires only demonstrations but derives rewards automatically.

\[ \pi_{k+1} = \arg\max_{\pi} \mathbb{E}_{\pi}[r(y,x)] - \beta D_{KL}(\pi \| \pi_k) \]
  • \(\pi_{k+1}\): Next policy to be learned
  • \(\pi_k\): Current policy (anchor)
  • \(r(y,x)\): Reward for output \(y\) given input \(x\)
  • \(\beta\): KL penalty coefficient (inverse temperature)
  • \(D_\text{KL}\): KL divergence constraining policy change
\[ \pi^*_{k+1}(y|x) \propto \pi_k(y|x) \exp\left(\frac{1}{\beta} r(y,x)\right) \]
  • \(\pi^*_{k+1}\): Optimal solution to trust-region problem
  • \(\pi_k(y|x)\): Current policy probability of \(y\) given \(x\)
  • \(\exp(r/\beta)\): Exponential re-weighting by reward, temperature-scaled
\[ r(y,x,c) = \log \pi(y|x,c) - \log \pi_k(y|x) \]
  • \(r(y,x,c)\): Implicit reward, derived by rearranging the optimal policy
  • \(\log \pi(y|x,c)\): Teacher log-probability (model with demonstration)
  • \(\log \pi_k(y|x)\): Student log-probability (model without demonstration)
\[ r_t = \log \pi(y_t|y_{<t},x,c) - \log \pi_k(y_t|y_{<t},x) \]
  • \(r_t\): Per-token implicit reward at position \(t\)
  • \(y_t\): Token at position \(t\)
  • \(y_{<t}\): All preceding tokens
  • \(\pi(y_t|y_{<t},x,c)\): Teacher's probability of token \(t\) given context and demo
  • \(\pi_k(y_t|y_{<t},x)\): Student's probability of token \(t\) given context only
\[ \nabla J = \mathbb{E}_{\pi_k}\left[r(y,x,c) \nabla \log \pi_k(y|x)\right] = \mathbb{E}_{\pi_k}\left[\log\frac{\pi(y|x,c)}{\pi_k(y|x)} \nabla \log \pi_k(y|x)\right] \]
  • \(\nabla J\): Policy gradient of the objective
  • \(\mathbb{E}_{\pi_k}\): Expectation under current student policy (on-policy)
  • \(r(y,x,c)\): Implicit reward (teacher-student log ratio)
  • \(\nabla \log \pi_k(y|x)\): Score function (gradient of log-probability)
Design Decisions
  • The ICL Assumption (teacher approximates optimal next policy) is what bridges distillation and RL. Without it, the log-ratio would just be a divergence measure, not a reward.
  • Token-level reward decomposition allows credit assignment to specific tokens rather than only scoring entire sequences, which improves learning efficiency.
  • The trust-region formulation naturally limits how much the policy can change per step, structurally preventing catastrophic forgetting without any explicit continual learning mechanism.

IRL-Equivalent Training Step (Python) 
# IRL-Equivalent Training Step
# This shows the RL interpretation of the same SDFT update

def sdft_as_rl_step(student, teacher, question, demo):
    # 1. On-policy rollout from current student
    trajectory = student.generate(question, do_sample=True, max_length=2048)
    tokens = tokenize(trajectory)
    
    # 2. Compute per-token implicit rewards
    teacher_input = format_with_demo(question, demo)
    teacher_logprobs = teacher.token_log_probs(tokens, context=teacher_input)
    student_logprobs = student.token_log_probs(tokens, context=question)
    
    per_token_rewards = teacher_logprobs - student_logprobs  # r_t
    sequence_reward = per_token_rewards.sum()  # r(y,x,c)
    
    # 3. Policy gradient (REINFORCE)
    # nabla J = r(y,x,c) * nabla log pi_k(y|x)
    # Equivalently: minimize reverse KL
    loss = -sequence_reward * student_logprobs.sum()
    # Or directly: loss = (student_logprobs - teacher_logprobs).mean()
    
    return loss

# Note: Both formulations yield identical gradients.
# The direct KL form is simpler to implement;
# the RL form provides interpretability (you can inspect per-token rewards).
Practical Tips ▼
  • You can log per-token rewards during training to see WHERE the model is learning. High-reward tokens indicate behaviors the demo taught that the student has not yet internalized.
  • The implicit reward naturally goes to zero as training converges (student matches teacher), providing a built-in convergence diagnostic.
  • Unlike explicit RL, there is no reward hacking risk because the reward is defined by the model's own predictions, not an external proxy.
  • The RL interpretation means standard RL diagnostics apply: monitor reward variance, check for entropy collapse, and watch for the policy ratio going to extremes.
Known Failure Modes ▼
  • Reward signal too weak: Per-token rewards are near zero even early in training, learning is slow Solution: The teacher's ICL capability may be too weak. Verify that the teacher with demonstration significantly outperforms the student without it. If not, use a better demonstration or a larger model.
  • Reward signal too strong: Very large per-token rewards, unstable gradients Solution: The student and teacher have diverged too far. Increase EMA alpha so the teacher tracks the student more closely, or reduce learning rate.
  • Credit assignment issues: Model learns surface patterns (formatting) but not deep task structure Solution: Inspect per-token rewards. If rewards are concentrated on formatting tokens (newlines, headers), the demonstration may be teaching style rather than substance. Use demonstrations that differ in content but share style with the student's current outputs.
§ 3

In-Context Learning Assumption and Validation

Key Insight

The method relies on one key assumption: showing the model an example answer makes it perform nearly optimally. Empirically, the base model jumps from 42% to 100% accuracy on tool use when given a single demonstration, validating this assumption.

The entire SDFT framework rests on a single critical assumption: when you show a large language model an example of what you want, the model's output becomes a good approximation of the ideal output. If this assumption fails, the teacher is not actually teaching anything useful, and training against it would be pointless or even harmful.

This assumption has two parts. First, the teacher must actually be good: it needs to produce near-optimal outputs when given the demonstration. Second, the teacher must not be too different from the student: if the demonstration causes the model to behave in a radically different way, the student would need to make dramatic changes to match it, which would destroy prior knowledge.

Think of it like asking a friend to demonstrate a dance move for you. The assumption works if (1) your friend can actually do the move well when shown a video of it, and (2) the move is not so different from what your friend already knows that they would need to completely change their style. If both hold, you can learn the move by watching your friend's version, which is naturally adapted to a style similar to your own.

The authors validate both parts empirically. On the ToolAlpaca benchmark, the base model solves only 42% of tasks independently, but when given a single demonstration in its context, it solves 100%. This confirms part one. For part two, they measure how much the model's output distribution changes when it sees the demonstration. Standard SFT targets deviate from the base model by 1.26 nats, but the teacher with a demonstration deviates by only 0.68 nats, nearly half. This means the teacher is excellent but still close to the student, exactly the sweet spot needed. The authors also manually inspected 50 teacher traces and confirmed they contained valid, original reasoning rather than simply copying the demonstration.

Core Idea

The teacher must be both good (near-optimal performance) and gentle (small distributional shift from the student). Empirically, demonstrations achieve 100% accuracy while shifting the distribution less than SFT targets do.

Analogy

Like asking a friend to demonstrate a dance move after watching a video: the assumption works if your friend can do the move well AND their style is close enough to yours that you can naturally learn from them.

Technical Details

The ICL Assumption formally states that \(\pi(y|x,c) \approx \pi^*_{k+1}(y|x)\), where \(\pi(y|x,c)\) is the teacher's output distribution conditioned on query \(x\) and demonstration \(c\), and \(\pi^*_{k+1}(y|x)\) is the optimal next policy under the trust-region RL formulation.

For this approximation to hold, two conditions must be satisfied simultaneously:

Condition 1 (Optimality): The teacher must achieve near-maximal reward. Formally, \(\mathbb{E}[r(y,x)]\) where \(y\) is sampled from \(\pi(y|x,c)\) should be close to \(\max_\pi \mathbb{E}[r(y,x)]\). The authors validate this on ToolAlpaca: the base Qwen2.5-7B-Instruct model achieves 42% accuracy without demonstrations, but \(\pi(y|x,c)\) with a single demonstration achieves 100%, demonstrating that ICL effectively closes the performance gap to the optimal policy.

Condition 2 (Minimal Deviation): The teacher must remain close to the current student in distribution space. Formally, \(D_\text{KL}(\pi(y|x,c) \| \pi_k(y|x))\) must be small relative to the trust-region constraint. The authors measure this empirically and find \(D_\text{KL} = 0.68\) nats between teacher and base model, compared to \(D_\text{KL} = 1.26\) nats between SFT targets and the base model. The teacher is nearly half the distributional distance from the base model compared to standard fine-tuning targets.

This dual condition has a geometric interpretation. In policy space, the optimal next policy \(\pi^*_{k+1}\) lies within the trust region around the current policy \(\pi_k\). The ICL Assumption says that \(\pi(y|x,c)\) also lies within (or very near) this trust region. If the teacher were too far away (high KL), the trust-region constraint would be violated, and the SDFT update would overshoot, potentially causing catastrophic forgetting.

The authors also address a potential concern: is the teacher simply copying the demonstration? Manual inspection of 50 traces shows that the teacher produces valid, original reasoning that is informed by but not copied from the demonstration. This is important because rote copying would not transfer generalizable knowledge to the student.

The assumption has known failure modes. At 3B parameters, where in-context learning capability is weaker, SDFT underperforms SFT by 3.3 points (Table 4). This directly corresponds to the Optimality condition failing: the smaller model cannot effectively leverage the demonstration, so \(\pi(y|x,c)\) is a poor approximation of \(\pi^*_{k+1}\). However, the assumption strengthens with scale: at 7B the gap is +4.0 in favor of SDFT, and at 14B it grows to +6.9, consistent with the well-documented scaling of ICL capabilities.

The validation approach itself is notable methodologically. Rather than assuming ICL works and hoping for the best, the authors provide concrete, falsifiable tests for both conditions. This allows practitioners to check whether SDFT is appropriate for their specific model and task before committing to the full training pipeline.

\[ \pi(y|x,c) \approx \pi^*_{k+1}(y|x) \]
  • \(\pi(y|x,c)\): Teacher distribution (model conditioned on query and demonstration)
  • \(\pi^*_{k+1}(y|x)\): Optimal next policy under trust-region RL
  • \(\approx\): The ICL Assumption — demo-conditioned model approximates the optimal update
\[ D_{KL}(\pi(\cdot|x,c) \| \pi_k(\cdot|x)) = 0.68 \text{ nats} \]
  • \(D_\text{KL}\): KL divergence measuring distributional distance
  • \(0.68\) nats: Empirical teacher-student divergence (vs. 1.26 nats for SFT)
Design Decisions
  • Both conditions (optimality and minimal deviation) must hold simultaneously. High accuracy alone is insufficient if the teacher distribution is too far from the student.
  • The 0.68 vs 1.26 nats comparison directly explains why SDFT causes less forgetting than SFT: the gradient signal is gentler.
  • Manual inspection of 50 traces was done to rule out the copying hypothesis, which would make the teacher a poor source of generalizable knowledge.
  • The failure at 3B parameters is not a bug but a principled limitation: SDFT should only be used when the base model has sufficiently strong ICL capability.

ICL Assumption Validation (Python) 
# Pre-training validation: Check if ICL Assumption holds

def validate_icl_assumption(model, eval_dataset, demos):
    # Condition 1: Optimality
    base_scores = []
    teacher_scores = []
    
    for question, gold_answer in eval_dataset:
        # Base model without demo
        base_output = model.generate(question)
        base_scores.append(evaluate(base_output, gold_answer))
        
        # Teacher: model with demo
        teacher_prompt = TEMPLATE.format(question=question, demo=demos[question])
        teacher_output = model.generate(teacher_prompt)
        teacher_scores.append(evaluate(teacher_output, gold_answer))
    
    print(f'Base accuracy: {mean(base_scores):.1%}')    # Expect ~40-60%
    print(f'Teacher accuracy: {mean(teacher_scores):.1%}')  # Expect ~90-100%
    
    if mean(teacher_scores) < 0.8:
        print('WARNING: ICL Assumption likely violated (Optimality).')
        print('Consider: larger model, better demos, or fall back to SFT.')
    
    # Condition 2: Minimal Deviation
    kl_values = []
    for question in eval_dataset:
        base_logprobs = model.log_probs(question)  # pi_k(y|x)
        teacher_logprobs = model.log_probs(
            TEMPLATE.format(question=question, demo=demos[question])
        )  # pi(y|x,c)
        
        # Estimate KL divergence via sampling
        kl = estimate_kl(teacher_logprobs, base_logprobs)
        kl_values.append(kl)
    
    mean_kl = mean(kl_values)
    print(f'Mean KL(teacher || student): {mean_kl:.2f} nats')  # Expect < 1.0
    
    if mean_kl > 1.5:
        print('WARNING: ICL Assumption likely violated (Deviation too large).')
        print('Teacher is too different from student. Risk of catastrophic forgetting.')
    
    return mean(base_scores), mean(teacher_scores), mean_kl
Practical Tips ▼
  • Always run this validation BEFORE committing to SDFT training. It takes minutes and can save hours of wasted compute.
  • If base accuracy is already high (>80%), SDFT may not help much because the implicit reward signal will be weak (teacher and student already agree).
  • If teacher accuracy is low (<80%), do not use SDFT. Fall back to SFT with curated data or use a stronger model as an external teacher.
  • The KL divergence check is a proxy for forgetting risk. If KL > 1.5 nats, expect significant forgetting even with SDFT.
  • Quality of demonstrations matters: use diverse, well-written examples. A single bad demo can make the teacher worse than the base model for that task.
Known Failure Modes ▼
  • ICL Assumption fails at small scale: SDFT underperforms SFT, especially on tasks requiring complex reasoning Solution: Use a model with >= 7B parameters. At 3B, ICL capability is insufficient to create a good teacher.
  • Demo quality is poor: Teacher accuracy with demo is lower than expected, or teacher outputs contain errors Solution: Curate demonstrations carefully. Use ground-truth or expert-verified examples. Test multiple demos and use the one that maximizes teacher accuracy.
  • KL divergence is too high: Teacher deviates > 1.5 nats from student, SDFT causes forgetting comparable to SFT Solution: The demonstration may be too different from the model's natural behavior. Try demonstrations that are closer to the model's style or use a shorter demo.
  • Teacher copies the demo: Teacher outputs contain verbatim phrases from the demonstration, student learns to parrot Solution: Manually inspect teacher traces. If copying is prevalent, use demos for different questions than the training questions (i.e., the demo should illustrate the format, not answer the specific question).
§ 4

Experiments & Results

Key Insight

When learning three tasks sequentially (Science QA, Tool Use, Medical), SDFT retains 64.5-65.4% accuracy on previously learned tasks compared to SFT's 53.4-60.2%, while also scoring higher on the new task (70.2% vs 66.2% on Science QA). For knowledge acquisition from Wikipedia 2025, SDFT achieves 89% strict accuracy vs SFT's 80%.

The core promise of SDFT is that a model can keep learning new things without forgetting old ones. The experiments test this in two complementary settings: learning new skills and acquiring new factual knowledge.

For skill learning, the authors train a single model on three tasks one after another: answering science questions, using tools via API calls, and answering medical questions. After learning all three, they check whether the model still remembers the earlier tasks. With standard fine-tuning, the model suffers catastrophic forgetting: it gets better at the latest task but loses 10-13 percentage points on tasks it learned earlier. SDFT avoids this, retaining performance on prior tasks while actually scoring higher on each new task too.

For knowledge acquisition, they test something qualitatively different: can the model absorb brand-new facts it has never seen? They use Wikipedia articles about 2025 natural disasters that post-date the model's training data. SDFT achieves 89% strict accuracy and 98% on out-of-distribution questions, compared to SFT's 80% and 80%. This shows SDFT is not just preserving old knowledge but actually learning new information more effectively.

The multi-task continual learning experiment is the most dramatic. Over a sequence of tasks, SDFT accumulates capabilities: each new task is learned without degrading previous ones. SFT, by contrast, shows the classic staircase pattern of catastrophic forgetting where each new task partially erases the last. Think of it like building with blocks: SDFT stacks blocks stably, while SFT keeps knocking over the tower every time it adds a new block.

Core Idea

SDFT simultaneously improves new-task performance and preserves old-task performance, achieving both goals better than standard fine-tuning achieves either one alone.

Analogy

Like building with blocks: SDFT stacks each new skill stably on top of the previous ones, while SFT keeps knocking over the tower every time it tries to add a new block.

Key Takeaway

Technical Details

The experiments are structured around two evaluation paradigms: skill learning (adapting to new task formats) and knowledge acquisition (absorbing new factual content).

Skill Learning (Tables 1 and 2)

The primary skill learning experiment uses Qwen2.5-7B-Instruct as the base model and trains sequentially on three tasks: Science QA (multiple-choice science questions), ToolAlpaca (API tool usage), and MedQA (medical question answering). After each task, the model is evaluated on both the current task and all prior tasks.

After training on Science QA (the first task), SDFT achieves 70.2% new-task accuracy versus SFT's 66.2%. Prior-task retention is measured by the model's performance on the instruction-following benchmark (proxy for general capability): SDFT retains 64.5% versus SFT's 53.4%. This 11-point gap in retention is the key finding.

The pattern continues through subsequent tasks. After Tool Use: SDFT achieves 70.6% new / 65.4% prior versus SFT's 63.2% / 56.0%. After Medical: SDFT achieves 40.2% new / 65.4% prior versus SFT's 35.5% / 60.2%. The prior-task retention numbers for SDFT are remarkably stable (64.5, 65.4, 65.4), while SFT shows a clear downward trend (53.4, 56.0, 60.2). Results are averaged over 3 seeds with 95% confidence intervals.

Baseline comparisons are comprehensive. DFT (distillation with importance sampling) performs comparably to SDFT on some tasks but is less consistent. SFT+Re-invoke (rehearsal by regenerating old-task data) partially mitigates forgetting but at additional computational cost. CPT (continued pre-training on raw text) shows the weakest new-task performance, confirming that task structure in demonstrations matters. Oracle RAG (retrieval with ground-truth context at inference time) represents an upper bound and is the only method that consistently outperforms SDFT.

Knowledge Acquisition (Table 3)

This experiment tests whether SDFT can inject genuinely new factual knowledge into a model. The dataset comprises Wikipedia articles about 2025 natural disasters (post-training-data events). Three evaluation categories are used:

  • Strict: Questions directly answerable from the articles. SDFT: 89%, SFT: 80%.
  • Lenient: Questions with partial information in the articles. SDFT: 100%, SFT: 95%.
  • Out-of-distribution (OOD): Questions requiring generalization beyond the articles. SDFT: 98%, SFT: 80%.

The OOD gap (98% vs 80%) is particularly significant. It suggests that SDFT does not just memorize facts from the demonstration but internalizes them in a way that supports generalization, consistent with the IRL interpretation where the model is learning a policy (how to reason about disasters) rather than memorizing specific answers.

Multi-Task Continual Learning (Figure 5)

The most comprehensive experiment trains on a longer sequence of tasks and measures cumulative performance. SDFT shows an accumulating pattern where each task is learned without degrading others, while SFT exhibits the classic catastrophic forgetting staircase. This figure is the strongest visual evidence for SDFT's continual learning capability.

\[ \text{Retention} = \frac{\text{Acc}_{\text{prior tasks after learning new task}}}{\text{Acc}_{\text{prior tasks before learning new task}}} \]
  • \(\text{Retention}\): Ratio measuring how much prior-task performance is preserved
  • \(\text{Acc}_\text{prior}\): Accuracy on previously learned tasks
Design Decisions
  • Three diverse tasks (Science, Tool Use, Medical) were chosen to test different aspects of learning: factual recall, procedural reasoning, and domain expertise.
  • Wikipedia 2025 articles were used for knowledge acquisition to ensure the facts genuinely post-date the model's training data, preventing contamination.
  • OOD evaluation in knowledge acquisition tests generalization, not just memorization, which is critical for distinguishing true knowledge internalization from surface-level pattern matching.
  • Oracle RAG is included as an upper bound to contextualize SDFT's performance: it shows what is achievable with perfect retrieval at inference time.

Multi-task Continual Learning Pipeline (Python) 
# Multi-task Continual Learning Pipeline

tasks = [
    {'name': 'science_qa', 'data': load_science_qa(), 'demos': load_science_demos()},
    {'name': 'tool_use',   'data': load_tool_alpaca(), 'demos': load_tool_demos()},
    {'name': 'medical',    'data': load_medqa(),       'demos': load_med_demos()},
]

model = load_model('Qwen/Qwen2.5-7B-Instruct')
results = {}

for task_idx, task in enumerate(tasks):
    # Train on current task using SDFT
    model = sdft_train(
        model=model,
        questions=task['data'],
        demos=task['demos'],
        lr=1e-5,
        ema_alpha=0.02,
        max_gen_length=2048
    )
    
    # Evaluate on current task
    current_acc = evaluate(model, task['data'].test_split)
    results[f'{task["name"]}_new'] = current_acc
    
    # Evaluate on ALL prior tasks (retention)
    for prev_idx in range(task_idx):
        prev_task = tasks[prev_idx]
        prior_acc = evaluate(model, prev_task['data'].test_split)
        results[f'{prev_task["name"]}_after_{task["name"]}'] = prior_acc
    
    # Evaluate general capability (instruction following)
    general_acc = evaluate_instruction_following(model)
    results[f'general_after_{task["name"]}'] = general_acc

print_results_table(results)

# Knowledge Acquisition Pipeline
def knowledge_acquisition_experiment(model, articles, eval_sets):
    # Convert articles to demo format
    demos = {q: extract_relevant_passage(articles, q) for q in train_questions}
    
    model = sdft_train(model, train_questions, demos)
    
    for eval_name, eval_set in eval_sets.items():  # strict, lenient, ood
        acc = evaluate(model, eval_set)
        print(f'{eval_name}: {acc:.0%}')
Practical Tips ▼
  • Task ordering can matter. Start with the task that is most different from the model's pre-training distribution, as later tasks benefit from the continual learning properties accumulating.
  • For knowledge acquisition, the demonstration should contain the actual source text (e.g., Wikipedia passage), not just a question-answer pair. The model needs to see the information to internalize it.
  • Monitor prior-task accuracy after EACH new task, not just at the end. A sudden drop after one specific task suggests that task's demonstrations may be too far from the model's distribution.
  • The OOD evaluation is the most informative metric for knowledge acquisition. High strict accuracy with low OOD accuracy suggests memorization rather than genuine knowledge internalization.
  • One demonstration per example is sufficient. Using multiple demonstrations did not show significant improvement and increases computational cost.
Known Failure Modes ▼
  • Catastrophic forgetting despite using SDFT: Prior-task accuracy drops by >5 points after learning a new task Solution: Check the ICL Assumption for the new task. If the teacher KL divergence is >1.5 nats, the update is too aggressive. Consider using a more relevant demonstration or reducing the learning rate.
  • Poor new-task performance: SDFT accuracy on the new task is lower than SFT Solution: Verify teacher accuracy with the demonstration. If <80%, the demonstration quality is the bottleneck. Also check that the model size is >= 7B.
  • Knowledge not generalizing (low OOD): High strict accuracy but low OOD accuracy, suggesting memorization Solution: Use demonstrations that emphasize reasoning and context, not just facts. Include 'thinking process' in the prompt template to encourage the teacher to show its reasoning.
  • Evaluation contamination: Suspiciously high accuracy on knowledge acquisition tasks Solution: Verify that knowledge source (e.g., Wikipedia articles) genuinely post-dates the model's training data cutoff. Use facts that are verifiably novel.
§ 5

Model Scaling & Reasoning Preservation

Key Insight

SDFT's advantage over SFT grows with model size: -3.3 points at 3B, +4.0 at 7B, +6.9 at 14B. On reasoning models, SDFT improves task accuracy to 43.7% while preserving reasoning depth, whereas SFT degrades to 23.5% and shortens reasoning chains.

One of the most important practical questions about any training method is: does it get better or worse as models get larger? SDFT gets dramatically better. At 3 billion parameters, SDFT actually performs slightly worse than standard fine-tuning, losing by about 3 points. But at 7 billion parameters it wins by 4 points, and at 14 billion it wins by nearly 7 points. The gap keeps growing.

This scaling behavior is not accidental. It directly reflects the in-context learning assumption that SDFT depends on. Smaller models are worse at learning from examples in their context window, so the teacher version of a 3B model is not much better than the student version. With a weak teacher, there is little useful signal to distill. Larger models are much better at in-context learning, so the teacher becomes a much stronger guide, and SDFT benefits proportionally.

The reasoning model experiments are equally striking. Recent 'thinking' models like Olmo-3-7B-Think produce long chains of reasoning before answering. When fine-tuned with SFT on a new task, the model's reasoning chains get dramatically shorter and its accuracy drops from a baseline to just 23.5%. The model essentially unlearns how to think deeply. SDFT, by contrast, improves accuracy to 43.7% while keeping the reasoning chains long and detailed.

This is like the difference between teaching someone a new subject by having them memorize answers (SFT, which overwrites their thinking habits) versus having them work through problems with a guide (SDFT, which adds knowledge while preserving their analytical approach). The second approach naturally preserves the student's reasoning ability because it never asks them to stop thinking.

Core Idea

SDFT's advantage scales with model size because larger models have stronger in-context learning. It also uniquely preserves reasoning depth in 'thinking' models, where SFT causes reasoning collapse.

Figure 5: SDFT benefits from model scale and shows genuine skill acquisition (not entropy collapse)
What This Shows

At 3B parameters, the model's ICL is too weak to produce a good teacher, so SFT is actually better. At 7B, SDFT overtakes SFT. At 14B, the gap widens to +6.9 points. This validates the theoretical mechanism: SDFT works because of strong ICL, and ICL improves with scale. Right panel addresses a potential critique: that SDFT's accuracy gains could be an artifact of entropy collapse (the model just becomes more confident, not more skilled).   • Understanding of pass@k: the probability that at least one of k independent samples is correct
  • Understanding of entropy collapse: the failure mode where a model becomes overconfident rather than more skilled

Common Confusions:

  • Why is SDFT worse than SFT at 3B?: SDFT's teacher is only as good as the model's in-context learning. At 3B parameters, ICL is too weak to produce informative teacher signals, so the self-distillation provides worse training signal than direct SFT on expert demonstrations.
  • What does pass@k measure exactly?: For each test problem, generate k independent samples. pass@k = 1 if at least one sample is correct, 0 otherwise. Averaged over all problems. Higher k means you're checking if the model CAN produce the right answer among many tries.

Key Takeaway

Technical Details

Scaling Experiments (Table 4)

The authors evaluate SDFT versus SFT across three model sizes in the Qwen2.5-Instruct family: 3B, 7B, and 14B parameters. The metric is the accuracy gap (SDFT minus SFT) on new-task performance averaged across the skill learning tasks.

At 3B parameters, SDFT underperforms SFT by 3.3 points. This is a principled failure: 3B models have limited in-context learning capability, so the teacher \(\pi(y|x,c)\) does not significantly outperform the student \(\pi_\theta(y|x)\). The ICL Assumption's Optimality condition is violated. At 7B, SDFT leads by +4.0 points, and at 14B by +6.9 points. The monotonically increasing gap directly tracks the well-documented scaling of ICL ability with model size.

This scaling behavior has important theoretical implications. It suggests that SDFT will become increasingly dominant as foundation models continue to scale. The method's reliance on ICL, often seen as a limitation, is actually a strength that converts model scale directly into better continual learning.

Reasoning Model Experiments (Table 5 and Figure 7)

The authors test SDFT on Olmo-3-7B-Think, a model specifically trained to produce extended chains of thought before answering. This is a particularly sensitive test case because reasoning models have a fragile internal structure: the long thinking chains are a learned behavior that can be easily disrupted.

SFT on tool-use tasks causes severe reasoning degradation. Task accuracy drops to 23.5% (lower than the base model's capability), and the average reasoning chain length decreases significantly. The model learns the new task format but at the cost of its reasoning ability, a form of catastrophic forgetting that affects not just prior task knowledge but the model's general cognitive strategy.

SDFT achieves 43.7% accuracy on the same task while preserving the model's reasoning depth. The generated reasoning chains remain long and detailed, and the model successfully integrates the new tool-use skills into its existing reasoning framework.

The mechanism is consistent with the theoretical analysis. SFT forces the model to match teacher-generated outputs exactly, including their (shorter, non-reasoning) format. This directly overwrites the reasoning chain generation behavior. SDFT, by contrast, asks the student to match the teacher's output distribution, which is only a gentle perturbation of the student's own distribution. The teacher, being the same reasoning model with a demonstration, naturally produces reasoning chains, so the student is never pressured to abandon its thinking process.

Figure 7 visualizes the reasoning chain characteristics before and after training. SFT-trained models show a clear shift toward shorter outputs with fewer reasoning steps. SDFT-trained models maintain the distribution of reasoning chain lengths, indicating that the thinking behavior is preserved.

This result has significant practical implications. As reasoning models become more prevalent (o1, DeepSeek-R1, etc.), the ability to add new capabilities without destroying reasoning chains becomes critical. SDFT is currently the only fine-tuning method demonstrated to achieve this.

\[ \Delta_{\text{SDFT-SFT}}(N) = \text{Acc}_{\text{SDFT}}(N) - \text{Acc}_{\text{SFT}}(N) \]
  • \(\Delta\): Accuracy gap between SDFT and SFT
  • \(N\): Model size in parameters
  • \(\text{Acc}\): Task accuracy (averaged across skill learning tasks)
\[ \Delta(3B) = -3.3, \quad \Delta(7B) = +4.0, \quad \Delta(14B) = +6.9 \]
  • \(-3.3\): SDFT underperforms at 3B (weak ICL)
  • \(+4.0\): SDFT advantage at 7B
  • \(+6.9\): SDFT advantage at 14B (strong ICL enables better self-distillation)
Design Decisions
  • Testing across 3B/7B/14B reveals the method's dependence on ICL capability and provides a practical minimum model size threshold.
  • Using a reasoning model (Olmo-3-7B-Think) specifically tests whether SDFT preserves fragile learned behaviors, not just factual knowledge.
  • Measuring reasoning chain length (not just accuracy) captures whether the model's cognitive strategy is preserved, a dimension SFT evaluations typically miss.

Practical Tips ▼
  • Do not use SDFT on models smaller than 7B parameters. The 3B failure is consistent and principled: weak ICL makes the teacher unhelpful.
  • For reasoning models, verify that the teacher (model + demo) produces reasoning chains similar in length and depth to the base model. If the demo causes the teacher to skip reasoning, the student will learn to skip it too.
  • When scaling up, keep EMA alpha the same. The authors do not report needing to adjust hyperparameters across model sizes.
  • For reasoning models, include a reasoning-style demonstration (one that shows extended thinking) rather than a direct answer. This ensures the teacher maintains the reasoning behavior.
  • The 14B model may require gradient checkpointing or reduced batch sizes to fit on a single H200. Use half-precision (bfloat16) throughout.
Known Failure Modes ▼
  • No scaling benefit: SDFT-SFT gap does not increase with model size Solution: Check that the larger model actually has better ICL capability on your specific task. Some tasks may not benefit from ICL regardless of scale.
  • Reasoning collapse despite SDFT: Reasoning chain lengths decrease during SDFT training on a reasoning model Solution: The demonstration may not include reasoning. Ensure the teacher prompt elicits full chain-of-thought responses. Add 'Show your complete thinking process step by step' to the template.
  • 14B model OOM: GPU memory error during on-policy generation with 14B model Solution: Use gradient checkpointing, reduce max_generation_length to 1024, or split generation and training into separate passes to reduce peak memory.
  • Reasoning model accuracy worse than base: Post-SDFT accuracy is lower than pre-training accuracy Solution: The task may conflict with the reasoning model's style. Verify that the teacher can actually solve the task with the demo before training.
§ 6

Why On-Policy Sampling Matters

Key Insight

Ablation experiments show a clear hierarchy: on-policy SDFT outperforms offline distillation, which outperforms SFT from teacher outputs. Both the self-distillation objective and on-policy sampling are independently important, and their combination is what makes SDFT work.

SDFT has two key ingredients that differ from standard training: it uses a distillation loss (matching the teacher's distribution instead of maximizing likelihood of specific outputs) and it uses on-policy sampling (the student generates its own outputs to train on, rather than using pre-generated data). The ablation experiments tease apart which ingredient matters more.

The authors compare three variants. First, on-policy SDFT: the full method where the student generates outputs and trains against the teacher's distribution. Second, offline distillation: the student trains against the teacher's distribution, but using pre-generated teacher outputs instead of its own. Third, SFT from teacher: standard supervised training on the teacher's generated outputs, with no distillation loss at all.

The results show a consistent ranking across tasks: on-policy SDFT is best, offline distillation is second, and SFT from teacher is worst. This tells us both ingredients are independently valuable. The distillation objective helps (offline distillation beats SFT from teacher) because matching a distribution is gentler than maximizing likelihood of specific sequences. On-policy sampling helps (on-policy SDFT beats offline distillation) because the student receives feedback on its own current behavior rather than on behaviors it might never actually produce.

Think of it like learning tennis. SFT is watching videos of a pro and trying to copy their exact movements. Offline distillation is having a coach describe the ideal form and adjusting toward it. On-policy SDFT is playing actual games while the coach gives you real-time feedback on your own shots. The last approach is most effective because the feedback is always relevant to what you are actually doing, not what someone else did.

Core Idea

On-policy sampling ensures the model gets feedback on its own behavior, not pre-generated data. Combined with the distillation objective (soft distribution matching rather than hard likelihood maximization), this produces the best learning signal.

Analogy

Like learning tennis: copying pro videos (SFT) is least effective, getting coached on ideal form (offline distillation) is better, but playing games with real-time coaching feedback on your own shots (on-policy SDFT) is best.

Figure 8: EMA teacher provides stable and effective training; alternatives fail
What This Shows

This ablation compares three choices for the teacher's parameters: (1) EMA(theta), an exponential moving average of the student parameters, (2) theta_0, the frozen base model parameters, and (3) theta, the current student parameters (teacher = student). EMA provides the best of both worlds: it tracks the student's learning progress (unlike the frozen base) while maintaining stability (unlike using the student directly). The frozen base model fails because it cannot adapt its teaching as the student improves - the gap between teacher and student stays fixed. Using the student directly as teacher leads to a degenerate feedback loop where errors compound, causing training instabilities and divergence around step 500.

Technical Details

Prerequisites:

  • Understanding of Exponential Moving Average (EMA): a smoothed running average of parameters that updates slowly
  • Understanding of why feedback loops can be unstable (using the student as its own teacher)

Common Confusions:

  • Why does using the student directly (theta) cause instability?: When teacher = student, the KL divergence between them is always zero at initialization. The 'teacher' provides no useful signal because it makes the same errors as the student. Any deviation amplifies through the feedback loop, causing divergence.
  • What is the EMA update rate?: The EMA teacher parameters are updated as EMA = alpha * EMA + (1-alpha) * student. A high alpha (e.g., 0.99) means the teacher changes slowly, providing a stable but progressively informed target.

Technical Details

The ablation study in Figure 6 systematically decomposes SDFT into its constituent components by testing three training variants on the same tasks:

Variant 1: SFT from Teacher (neither distillation objective nor on-policy sampling) — The teacher generates outputs using \(\pi(y|x,c)\), and the student is trained to maximize log-likelihood of these fixed outputs: \(\mathcal{L}_\text{SFT} = -\mathbb{E}[\log \pi_\theta(y|x)]\) where \(y\) is sampled from the teacher. This is standard SFT, just using teacher-generated data instead of human-written data.

Variant 2: Offline Distillation (distillation objective, but not on-policy) — The teacher pre-generates outputs, and the student trains on the KL divergence between its own distribution and the teacher's, but evaluated on the teacher's pre-generated trajectories rather than the student's own: \(\mathcal{L}_\text{offline} = D_\text{KL}(\pi_\theta(y|x) \| \pi(y|x,c))\) evaluated on \(y \sim \pi(\cdot|x,c)\). This uses the softer distillation objective but the trajectories come from the teacher's (possibly outdated or irrelevant) behavior.

Variant 3: On-Policy SDFT (both distillation objective and on-policy sampling) — The full method where the student generates its own trajectories and the KL divergence is computed on these student-generated outputs: \(\mathcal{L}_\text{SDFT} = D_\text{KL}(\pi_\theta(y|x) \| \pi(y|x,c))\) evaluated on \(y \sim \pi_\theta(\cdot|x)\).

The theoretical basis for why on-policy matters comes from the IRL interpretation. The policy gradient is an expectation under the current policy: \(\nabla J = \mathbb{E}_{\pi_k}[r(y,x,c) \nabla \log \pi_k(y|x)]\). When this expectation is estimated using samples from \(\pi_k\) (on-policy), the gradient estimator is unbiased. When samples come from a different distribution (the teacher, in offline mode), the estimator is biased. This bias can point the gradient in the wrong direction, especially when the student and teacher distributions have diverged.

There is also a coverage argument. On-policy sampling ensures the student sees outputs it would actually generate. If the student has a particular failure mode (e.g., a systematic error in tool-use syntax), on-policy sampling will expose this failure mode and the teacher's distribution will provide corrective signal exactly where it is needed. Offline sampling from the teacher may never generate outputs that exhibit the student's specific failure modes, so those errors go uncorrected.

The consistent ranking (on-policy SDFT > offline distillation > SFT from teacher) across all tasks provides strong evidence that both components contribute independently. The gap between offline distillation and SFT from teacher isolates the value of the soft distillation objective. The gap between on-policy SDFT and offline distillation isolates the value of on-policy sampling. In both cases, the gap is significant and consistent.

This ablation also connects to the broader literature on on-policy versus off-policy methods in RL. On-policy methods (REINFORCE, PPO) are known to be more stable but less sample-efficient than off-policy methods (DQN, SAC). In the SDFT context, stability is more important than sample efficiency because the primary goal is continual learning without forgetting, which requires conservative, stable updates.

\[ \mathcal{L}_{\text{SFT}} = -\mathbb{E}_{y \sim \pi(\cdot|x,c)}[\log \pi_\theta(y|x)] \]
  • \(\mathcal{L}_\text{SFT}\): Standard supervised fine-tuning loss
  • \(y \sim \pi(\cdot|x,c)\): Outputs sampled from teacher (fixed, pre-generated)
  • \(\log \pi_\theta(y|x)\): Student's log-likelihood of teacher's output
\[ \mathcal{L}_{\text{offline}} = D_{KL}(\pi_\theta(\cdot|x) \| \pi(\cdot|x,c)) \bigg|_{y \sim \pi(\cdot|x,c)} \]
  • \(\mathcal{L}_\text{offline}\): Offline distillation loss (KL on teacher-generated trajectories)
  • \(y \sim \pi(\cdot|x,c)\): Trajectories from teacher, not student
\[ \mathcal{L}_{\text{SDFT}} = D_{KL}(\pi_\theta(\cdot|x) \| \pi(\cdot|x,c)) \bigg|_{y \sim \pi_\theta(\cdot|x)} \]
  • \(\mathcal{L}_\text{SDFT}\): On-policy SDFT loss (KL on student-generated trajectories)
  • \(y \sim \pi_\theta(\cdot|x)\): Trajectories from student (on-policy)
\[ \text{Performance ranking: } \mathcal{L}_{\text{SDFT}} > \mathcal{L}_{\text{offline}} > \mathcal{L}_{\text{SFT}} \]
  • \(>\): Produces better task performance and retention
Design Decisions
  • Three variants were chosen to isolate each component's contribution independently: SFT tests neither, offline tests distillation alone, on-policy tests both.
  • The same teacher and demonstrations are used across all three variants to ensure a fair comparison; only the training objective and sampling strategy differ.
  • On-policy sampling adds ~2.5x FLOPs overhead (generation at each step) but the performance gain justifies the cost.

Ablation: Three Training Variants (Python) 
# Ablation: Three Training Variants

def run_ablation(model, questions, demos):
    teacher = deepcopy(model)
    results = {}
    
    # ---- Variant 1: SFT from Teacher ----
    # Pre-generate teacher outputs
    teacher_outputs = {}
    for q, d in zip(questions, demos):
        prompt = TEMPLATE.format(question=q, demo=d)
        teacher_outputs[q] = teacher.generate(prompt, max_length=2048)
    
    sft_model = deepcopy(model)
    for q in questions:
        # Standard max-likelihood on teacher outputs
        loss = -sft_model.log_prob(teacher_outputs[q], context=q).mean()
        loss.backward()
        optimizer.step()
    results['sft_from_teacher'] = evaluate(sft_model)
    
    # ---- Variant 2: Offline Distillation ----
    offline_model = deepcopy(model)
    for q, d in zip(questions, demos):
        # KL divergence but on TEACHER-generated trajectories
        y = teacher_outputs[q]  # Pre-generated, fixed
        student_lp = offline_model.log_prob(y, context=q)
        teacher_lp = teacher.log_prob(y, context=TEMPLATE.format(question=q, demo=d))
        loss = (student_lp - teacher_lp).mean()  # Reverse KL on teacher trajectories
        loss.backward()
        optimizer.step()
    results['offline_distillation'] = evaluate(offline_model)
    
    # ---- Variant 3: On-Policy SDFT (full method) ----
    sdft_model = deepcopy(model)
    sdft_teacher = deepcopy(model)
    for q, d in zip(questions, demos):
        # Student generates ON-POLICY trajectories
        with torch.no_grad():
            y = sdft_model.generate(q, do_sample=True, max_length=2048)
        
        student_lp = sdft_model.log_prob(y, context=q)
        teacher_lp = sdft_teacher.log_prob(
            y, context=TEMPLATE.format(question=q, demo=d)
        )
        loss = (student_lp - teacher_lp).mean()  # Reverse KL on student trajectories
        loss.backward()
        optimizer.step()
        
        # EMA update teacher
        ema_update(sdft_teacher, sdft_model, alpha=0.02)
    results['on_policy_sdft'] = evaluate(sdft_model)
    
    # Expected ranking: on_policy_sdft > offline_distillation > sft_from_teacher
    return results
Practical Tips ▼
  • If compute budget is very tight, offline distillation is a reasonable compromise: it captures most of the benefit of the distillation objective without the on-policy generation cost.
  • When running the ablation yourself, use the SAME teacher outputs for SFT-from-teacher and offline distillation to ensure a fair comparison. Only the loss function should differ.
  • The ~4x wall-clock overhead of on-policy SDFT can be reduced by generating shorter sequences (reduce max_generation_length) or by batching generation across multiple examples.
  • Monitor the distribution mismatch between student and teacher trajectories in the offline variant. If it grows large, the offline approach will degrade and the gap to on-policy will widen.
  • The on-policy computational cost can potentially replace multi-stage pipelines (SFT + RL), making the total pipeline cost comparable while being simpler to implement.
Known Failure Modes ▼
  • Offline distillation performs as poorly as SFT: No benefit from the distillation objective in the offline setting Solution: The student and teacher may have already diverged too much. Pre-generate teacher outputs from a model checkpoint closer to the current student, or use importance sampling correction (DFT approach).
  • On-policy SDFT is slower than expected: Wall-clock time is >6x SFT instead of ~4x Solution: Check that generation is batched efficiently. Use vLLM or other optimized inference engines for the on-policy generation step. Avoid generating one example at a time.
  • Ablation results inconsistent across tasks: The ranking changes depending on the task Solution: Some tasks may have such strong teacher signals that even offline distillation captures most of the benefit. Focus on tasks where the student-teacher gap is moderate (KL ~0.5-1.5 nats) for the clearest ablation signal.
§ 7

Insights & Connections

In-context learning is a free implicit reward function

The paper's deepest insight is that ICL creates an asymmetry: conditioning a model on a demonstration tells it what to do without changing its weights, and the gap between the conditioned and unconditioned model defines an implicit reward. This means every model with strong ICL capabilities already contains its own reward signal for any task it can learn in-context -- you just need to extract it via self-distillation. This reframes ICL not merely as an inference-time capability but as a latent training signal.

Implications:

  • Reward engineering may be unnecessary for many fine-tuning tasks -- the model's own ICL provides the signal
  • The quality ceiling for SDFT is set by the model's ICL quality, creating a direct link between pre-training quality and fine-tuning potential
  • This suggests a new lens for evaluating foundation models: how good is their ICL as a proxy for fine-tunability?
  • Future work combining SDFT with explicit rewards could get the best of both worlds

Evidence: The demonstration-conditioned teacher achieves 100% accuracy on tool use while staying at only 0.68 nats KL from the base model (vs SFT at 1.26 nats), and the formal equivalence to trust-region RL is shown in Equations 1-6

On-policy learning from demonstrations is qualitatively different from better demonstrations

A natural objection to SDFT is that it simply creates a better teacher. The ablation in Section 4.6 decisively refutes this: even when using the same high-quality teacher, offline distillation and SFT-from-teacher both significantly underperform on-policy SDFT. The on-policy nature -- training on the student's own generated trajectories -- is the critical ingredient, not teacher quality. This validates the theoretical prediction from DAgger/Ross et al. that on-policy correction of the student's actual error distribution is fundamentally superior to training on any fixed data distribution.

Implications:

  • Simply generating better training data (e.g., with stronger models) cannot substitute for on-policy learning
  • The compounding error problem from offline imitation learning is a real and measurable phenomenon in LLM fine-tuning
  • This provides strong empirical support for the theoretical on-policy advantage that has been argued since DAgger (2011)
  • Practitioners should not expect data augmentation or synthetic data to close the gap with on-policy methods

Evidence: Figure 6 shows on-policy SDFT reaching ~70% accuracy while offline distillation from the same teacher plateaus at ~60% and SFT from teacher at ~55%, with the gap widening over training

Self-distillation preserves generation patterns that SFT destroys

The reasoning model experiment (Table 2) reveals something subtle: SFT does not just forget old knowledge -- it actively destroys the model's learned generation patterns. When a reasoning model (Olmo-3-7B-Think) is fine-tuned with answer-only data via SFT, it loses its chain-of-thought behavior (response length drops from 4612 to 3273 tokens) and accuracy actually degrades below the base model (23.5% vs 31.2%). SDFT avoids this because the teacher is the model itself conditioned on demonstrations, so it naturally preserves the model's internal reasoning style while adapting to the new task.

Implications:

  • SFT is not just suboptimal -- it can be actively harmful when demonstration format differs from the model's natural generation style
  • This has major implications for post-training reasoning models, where chain-of-thought traces are expensive to collect
  • SDFT enables fine-tuning with answer-only data while preserving reasoning depth, dramatically reducing annotation costs
  • The mechanism suggests SDFT could be valuable for any fine-tuning where the target format is sparser than the model's natural output

Evidence: Olmo-3-7B-Think accuracy: base 31.2%, SFT 23.5% (worse than base), SDFT 43.7% (12.5 points above base). Average token count: base 4612, SFT 3273 (collapsed), SDFT 4180 (preserved)

The ICL-SDFT relationship creates a positive scaling feedback loop

SDFT's effectiveness is gated by ICL quality, and ICL improves with model scale. This creates a virtuous cycle where larger models benefit disproportionately from SDFT. At 3B, ICL is too weak and SDFT actually underperforms SFT by 3.3 points. But at 7B the gap flips to +4.0, and at 14B it reaches +6.9 -- a monotonically increasing trend. This is not merely a 'bigger is better' result; it reveals a threshold effect where SDFT transitions from harmful to transformative as ICL capabilities cross a critical level.

Implications:

  • SDFT will likely become even more powerful with future, larger models
  • There is a minimum model capability threshold below which SDFT should not be used
  • The scaling trend suggests SDFT could eventually surpass methods that currently require explicit reward engineering
  • Model developers should prioritize ICL quality during pre-training to unlock better fine-tuning via SDFT

Evidence: Figure 5 (left): SDFT-SFT gap is -3.3 at Qwen2.5-3B, +4.0 at Qwen2.5-7B, +6.9 at Qwen2.5-14B, showing monotonic improvement with scale

DAgger / On-policy imitation learning (Ross et al., 2011) SDFT is essentially DAgger for LLMs, where the oracle/expert is replaced by the model's own ICL-conditioned version Eliminates the need for an external oracle by using self-conditioning, making on-policy imitation learning self-contained
Context distillation (Snell et al., 2022; Bai et al., 2022) Both distill knowledge from a context-conditioned model into an unconditioned one Makes distillation on-policy (training on student's own trajectories) and uses instance-specific demonstrations rather than fixed prompts
GRPO / Trust-region RL (Schulman et al., 2015) SDFT's theoretical formulation shows it is equivalent to trust-region RL with an implicit reward Derives the reward implicitly from ICL rather than requiring explicit reward specification; needs only 1 generation per prompt vs GRPO's group sampling
Inverse Reinforcement Learning (Ng et al., 2000; Ziebart et al., 2008) Both recover a learning signal from demonstrations without an explicit reward Avoids the ill-posedness and scalability issues of traditional IRL by using ICL as a natural structural prior
On-policy forgetting reduction (Shenfeld et al., 2025; Chen et al., 2025) Builds on the empirical finding that on-policy RL reduces catastrophic forgetting Extends this benefit to the demonstration-only regime where no reward function is available

Future Directions Enabled

  • SDFT as initialization for RL fine-tuning: The paper shows SDFT improves pass@k uniformly, meaning it creates a better starting policy. Using SDFT first, then reward-based RL, could yield compound benefits. The authors explicitly suggest this combination.
  • Continual learning pipelines in production: SDFT enables sequential skill accumulation without forgetting, making it practical to update deployed models with new capabilities over time rather than retraining from scratch.
  • Low-annotation fine-tuning of reasoning models: Since SDFT preserves reasoning patterns with answer-only data, it dramatically reduces the need for expensive chain-of-thought annotations when adapting reasoning models to new domains.
  • Self-improving model architectures: The ICL-as-implicit-reward concept could be extended to settings where the model generates its own demonstrations from experience, creating a loop of self-improvement without external supervision.
  • Knowledge injection without RAG dependency: SDFT achieves 89/100/98% accuracy (strict/lenient/OOD) approaching Oracle RAG's 91/100/100%, suggesting it could replace or complement RAG for stable knowledge updates.

Related Fields

  • Robotics / Imitation Learning: SDFT's theoretical roots in DAgger make it directly applicable to robotic policy learning from demonstrations. The self-conditioning trick could work for any agent with in-context adaptation capabilities.
  • Continual Learning / Lifelong Learning: SDFT provides a new mechanism for catastrophic forgetting prevention that is complementary to existing approaches like EWC, replay buffers, or architectural methods. It achieves forgetting reduction through the learning dynamics themselves rather than explicit regularization.
  • Knowledge Management / Enterprise AI: The knowledge acquisition results suggest SDFT could be used for enterprise knowledge updates -- teaching models about new products, policies, or domain knowledge -- with better OOD generalization than SFT and without RAG infrastructure.
  • Cognitive Science / Learning Theory: The self-distillation mechanism has parallels to human learning: seeing an example (ICL) is different from internalizing it (weight updates). The paper's framework formalizes how 'understanding by example' can be converted into permanent capability.
