Limitations & Future Work

Acknowledged Limitations

Requires strong in-context learning capabilities

At 3B parameters, SDFT underperforms SFT because the model's ICL is too weak to provide meaningful teacher signals. This sets a hard minimum model size requirement.

Severity: Moderate -- most production models are 7B+ where SDFT works well

Approximately 2.5x FLOPs and 4x wall-clock compute cost

On-policy rollouts during training are expensive. However, the authors note this compares favorably to multi-stage approaches like SFT+Re-invoke that require additional training phases.

Severity: Moderate -- may be offset by eliminating the need for separate forgetting-mitigation stages

Learned artifacts from teacher phrasing

The student can inherit phrases like 'Based on the text...' from the demonstration-conditioned teacher, even though it receives no such context. The authors use first-token loss masking as a heuristic fix.

Severity: Low -- practical workaround exists but a principled solution is missing

Cannot enable fundamental generation pattern shifts

SDFT works for acquiring new skills/knowledge while preserving existing patterns, but fails when the desired behavior requires fundamentally different generation patterns (e.g., adding chain-of-thought to a non-reasoning model).

Severity: Moderate -- limits SDFT to incremental adaptations rather than transformative changes

Not Addressed in Paper

Single model family tested for most experiments

Nearly all results use Qwen2.5-Instruct. While the reasoning experiment uses Olmo-3-7B-Think, broader validation across architectures (Llama, Mistral, Gemma) would strengthen the claims.

Potential Mitigation: Community replication across model families; the method is simple enough that this should be straightforward

Limited task diversity in skill learning

Three skill tasks (Science QA, Tool Use, Medical) are all relatively structured. Performance on more open-ended or creative tasks is unknown.

Potential Mitigation: Evaluate on writing, summarization, or dialogue tasks where demonstration quality and format vary more

Teacher context prompt sensitivity

The paper uses a single, hand-crafted prompt template for teacher conditioning. How sensitive are results to this prompt? Could better prompts yield much larger gains?

Potential Mitigation: Ablate over multiple prompt formats; explore automated prompt optimization for the teacher

No comparison with parameter-efficient methods

All experiments use full fine-tuning. Interaction between SDFT and LoRA/QLoRA is unexplored, yet parameter-efficient methods are the practical default for most practitioners.

Potential Mitigation: Evaluate SDFT with LoRA adapters to determine if the on-policy benefits transfer to parameter-efficient settings

Long-horizon forgetting not fully eliminated

While Figure 3 shows SDFT dramatically outperforms SFT on sequential learning, some degradation in prior capabilities still occurs. The paper acknowledges this but does not quantify the remaining gap.

Potential Mitigation: Combine SDFT with explicit forgetting prevention methods (replay, EWC) for even stronger continual learning

Open Questions

  • What is the exact minimum ICL quality threshold needed for SDFT to outperform SFT? Is it model-size-dependent or can it be measured independently?
  • Can SDFT be combined with parameter-efficient fine-tuning (LoRA), and does the on-policy benefit survive the low-rank constraint?
  • How does SDFT perform when demonstrations are noisy, suboptimal, or contradictory?
  • Could the implicit reward formulation be made explicit and combined with additional reward signals for hybrid SDFT+RL training?
  • Does SDFT work for multi-modal models where ICL operates across modalities (e.g., image-text)?
  • What happens when SDFT is applied for many more sequential tasks (10+, 50+) -- does the forgetting-free property hold at longer horizons?
  • Can the teacher phrasing leakage problem be solved by training on the divergence at the logit level rather than the sequence level?

When to Use SDFT

Recommended Use Cases
  • Teaching new skills to a production model (7B+) without degrading existing capabilities
  • Injecting new factual knowledge that needs to generalize beyond memorized Q&A pairs
  • Sequential multi-task learning where a single model must accumulate capabilities over time
  • Fine-tuning reasoning models when only answer-level (not chain-of-thought) supervision is available
  • Any setting where SFT causes unacceptable catastrophic forgetting of prior capabilities
  • When you want better OOD generalization than SFT provides from the same demonstration data
When NOT to Use SDFT
  • Models smaller than ~7B parameters where ICL capabilities are too weak
  • When the desired behavior requires a fundamental shift in generation patterns (e.g., adding CoT to a non-reasoning model)
  • Extremely compute-constrained settings where 2.5x FLOPs overhead is prohibitive
  • Tasks where explicit reward functions are available -- standard RL may be more direct and effective
  • When you need the model to exactly reproduce demonstration format/style rather than capture underlying intent
  • Single-shot fine-tuning where forgetting is not a concern and maximum new-task accuracy is the only goal

Implementation Priority

Step-by-Step Implementation Guide
  1. 1. Verify your base model has strong ICL: test demonstration-conditioned accuracy before committing to SDFT
  2. 2. Use an EMA teacher (not frozen base or current student) -- this is critical for training stability
  3. 3. Use the analytic per-token KL gradient estimator over alternatives (lower variance, simpler, best performance in ablations)
  4. 4. Single trajectory per prompt is sufficient -- multiple samples add cost without measurable benefit
  5. 5. Train for 2+ epochs (SDFT benefits from multiple epochs unlike SFT which overfits after 1)
  6. 6. Mask loss over initial tokens to prevent teacher phrasing leakage artifacts
  7. 7. Consider SDFT as a first stage before RL fine-tuning if you also have reward signals available

Appendix A

Forward vs Reverse KL Divergence & GRPO

KL divergence is central to SDFT's objective and to modern RLHF/GRPO training. This appendix unpacks the two directions of KL, how they're computed from model logits, and the practical approximation used in GRPO.

A.1 — Forward vs Reverse KL Divergence

KL divergence is asymmetric: \(\text{KL}(P \| Q) \neq \text{KL}(Q \| P)\). The two directions have fundamentally different optimization behaviors.

\[\text{KL}(P \| Q) = \sum_x P(x) \left[\log P(x) - \log Q(x)\right]\]
General KL divergence definition
Property Forward KL — \(\text{KL}(P \| Q)\) Reverse KL — \(\text{KL}(Q \| P)\)
Also called Mean-seeking / moment projection Mode-seeking / information projection
Objective Fit \(Q\) to cover all of \(P\) Fit \(Q\) to concentrate where \(P\) is high
Penalty Heavy penalty when \(P(x) > 0\) but \(Q(x) \approx 0\) Heavy penalty when \(Q(x) > 0\) but \(P(x) \approx 0\)
Behavior \(Q\) spreads out to cover all modes → over-dispersed \(Q\) locks onto dominant mode(s) → under-dispersed
Typical use Variational inference (ELBO) Policy optimization (RLHF, PPO, GRPO, SDFT)
Intuition

Forward KL: \(Q\) tries to cover \(P\) everywhere → mean-seeking (over-dispersed). Like a security camera that must see every corner.

Reverse KL: \(Q\) avoids placing mass where \(P\) is low → mode-seeking (under-dispersed). Like a spotlight that locks onto the brightest spot.

Why SDFT uses reverse KL

SDFT minimizes \(\text{KL}(\pi_\text{student} \| \pi_\text{teacher})\) — the reverse KL. This is mode-seeking: the student concentrates on the high-probability outputs of the teacher rather than trying to cover the teacher's full distribution. This is exactly what you want when learning a skill — you want the student to produce confident, high-quality outputs, not hedge across all possibilities.

Crucially, SDFT computes this on student-generated (on-policy) samples, which the paper proves is equivalent to on-policy RL with an implicit reward.

A.2 — From Logits to KL Divergence

Language models output logits — raw unnormalized scores over the vocabulary at each token position. Here's the pipeline from logits to a KL loss term.

Step 1: Logits → Probabilities

Apply softmax to convert logits \(z\) into a probability distribution:

\[\pi_\theta(t_i \mid t_{<i}) = \frac{e^{z_i}}{\sum_j e^{z_j}}\]
Softmax over vocabulary at each position

In practice, work in log-space for numerical stability: log_probs = log_softmax(logits)

Step 2: Compute per-token KL

Run the same input through both the current policy \(\pi_\theta\) and the reference policy \(\pi_\text{ref}\). The exact per-token KL sums over the full vocabulary:

\[\text{KL}(\pi_\theta \| \pi_\text{ref}) = \sum_{v \in \mathcal{V}} \pi_\theta(v) \left[\log \pi_\theta(v) - \log \pi_\text{ref}(v)\right]\]
Full KL over vocabulary (expensive)

In practice, since you're computing this along the tokens actually generated (not the full vocabulary), a simplified unbiased estimator is commonly used:

\[\hat{\text{KL}}_t = \log \pi_\theta(t_i \mid t_{<i}) - \log \pi_\text{ref}(t_i \mid t_{<i})\]
Single-sample KL estimator — just the log-prob difference at the sampled token

Step 3: Use in the loss (GRPO example)

GRPO (Group Relative Policy Optimization) uses a reverse KL penalty \(\text{KL}(\pi_\theta \| \pi_\text{ref})\) — the same direction as PPO/RLHF. The objective roughly looks like:

\[\mathcal{L} = -\mathbb{E}\left[\hat{A}_i \cdot \min\left(\frac{\pi_\theta}{\pi_\text{old}}, \text{clip}(\ldots)\right)\right] + \beta \cdot \text{KL}\]
GRPO objective: clipped policy gradient + KL regularization toward reference
  • \(\hat{A}_i\) — advantage estimate (group-relative in GRPO)
  • \(\pi_\text{old}\) — the policy that generated the rollouts
  • \(\beta\) — coefficient controlling how strongly KL regularizes the policy toward \(\pi_\text{ref}\)
PYTHON — From logits to per-token KL
# Forward pass through both models on the same tokens
logits_policy = policy_model(input_ids).logits
logits_ref = ref_model(input_ids).logits

# Convert to log-probabilities (numerically stable)
log_probs_policy = F.log_softmax(logits_policy, dim=-1)
log_probs_ref = F.log_softmax(logits_ref, dim=-1)

# Gather log-probs for the actual generated tokens
token_log_prob_policy = log_probs_policy.gather(
    -1, generated_ids.unsqueeze(-1)
).squeeze(-1)  # shape: (batch, seq_len)
token_log_prob_ref = log_probs_ref.gather(
    -1, generated_ids.unsqueeze(-1)
).squeeze(-1)

# Per-token KL estimate (naive single-sample)
kl = token_log_prob_policy - token_log_prob_ref  # shape: (batch, seq_len)
Key insight

You don't need to sum over the full vocabulary — the single-sample estimator (log-prob difference at the sampled token) is an unbiased estimate of the KL and is much cheaper to compute.

A.3 — Schulman's KL Approximation (used in GRPO)

The GRPO paper and its implementations (TRL, DeepSeek-R1) use an improved KL approximation proposed by Schulman, sometimes called the k3 estimator:

\[\hat{\text{KL}} = \frac{\pi_\text{ref}(t_i)}{\pi_\theta(t_i)} - \log \frac{\pi_\text{ref}(t_i)}{\pi_\theta(t_i)} - 1\]
Schulman's KL approximation (ratio form)

Equivalently, letting \(r = \log \pi_\text{ref} - \log \pi_\theta\):

\[\hat{\text{KL}} = e^{r} - r - 1\]
Schulman's KL in log-ratio form — \(f(r) = e^r - r - 1\)
Property Naive estimator
\(\log \pi_\theta - \log \pi_\text{ref}\)		 Schulman (k3) estimator
\(e^r - r - 1\)
Non-negativity Can go negative for individual tokens Always \(\geq 0\) (since \(e^x - x - 1 \geq 0\) for all \(x\))
Zero when equal Yes, when \(\pi_\theta = \pi_\text{ref}\) Yes, when \(\pi_\theta = \pi_\text{ref}\)
Variance Can have high variance Lower variance, better behaved
Gradient behavior Linear penalty Stronger gradients when policy drifts far from reference
Interpretation First-order approximation Second-order approximation accounting for both KL directions
PYTHON — Schulman's KL approximation (as used in DeepSeek-R1 / TRL GRPO)
# Per-token log-prob ratio
log_ratio = log_probs_ref - log_probs_policy  # r = log _ref - log _

# Schulman's k3 estimator: always non-negative
kl = torch.exp(log_ratio) - log_ratio - 1     # e^r - r - 1  0

# Average over tokens, then over batch
kl_loss = kl.mean()
Connection to SDFT

While GRPO uses \(\text{KL}(\pi_\theta \| \pi_\text{ref})\) as a regularizer (preventing drift from the base model), SDFT uses reverse KL as the primary objective — minimizing \(\text{KL}(\pi_\text{student} \| \pi_\text{teacher})\) where the teacher is the same model conditioned on demonstrations. Both leverage reverse KL's mode-seeking property, but for different purposes: GRPO constrains exploration; SDFT drives skill acquisition from demonstrations without reward engineering.
